<subSubSection box="[366,1222,1022,1049]" pageId="27" pageNumber="121" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="27.[366,1222,1022,1049]" box="[366,1222,1022,1049]" pageId="27" pageNumber="121">
Tribe 
<taxonomicName authority="Stein, 1907" authorityName="Stein" authorityYear="1907" box="[435,676,1022,1048]" family="Muscidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="121" rank="tribe" tribe="Eginiini">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[435,534,1022,1048]" pageId="27" pageNumber="121">Eginiini</emphasis>
Stein, 1907
</taxonomicName>
[Syllegopterini Brauer &amp; Bergenstamm 1889]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="27" pageNumber="121" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="27.[189,1398,1087,1149]" pageId="27" pageNumber="121">
Adult morphology and larval biology leave no doubt that this small tribe is monophyletic (
<bibRefCitation author="Michelsen V." pageId="27" pageNumber="121" pagination="361 - 376" refId="ref14929" refString="Michelsen V. 2007. Eginia ocypterata (Meigen) (Diptera: Muscidae), an overlooked West Palaearctic parasitoid of Diplopoda, with an update of its known occurrence in Europe. Studia Dipterologica 13: 361 - 376." type="journal article" year="2007">Michelsen 2007</bibRefCitation>
). Species from two out of four recognized genera (
<tableCitation box="[848,935,1123,1149]" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="5.[189,258,265,291]" captionTargetBox="[238,1379,394,1980]" captionText="Table 1 (continued on next 4 pages). Summary of vein C chaetotaxy with respect to multistate characterA for genus-group taxa of Fanniidae Schnabel &amp; Dziedcicki, 1911 and Muscidae Latreille, 1802. Examined genera highlighted in yellow. See ‘Material and methods’ for explanation of character states A0–8." pageId="27" pageNumber="121">Table 1</tableCitation>
) were examined.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[189,947,1196,1222]" box="[189,947,1196,1222]" pageId="27" pageNumber="121">
<emphasis box="[189,199,1197,1222]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="121">•</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Robineau-Desvoidy, 1830" authorityName="Robineau-Desvoidy" authorityYear="1830" box="[214,608,1196,1222]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Eginia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[214,292,1197,1222]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="121">Eginia</emphasis>
Robineau-Desvoidy, 1830
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Malloch, 1921" authorityName="Malloch" authorityYear="1921" box="[620,947,1196,1222]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Xenotachina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[620,768,1196,1222]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="121">Xenotachina</emphasis>
Malloch, 1921
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[189,1399,1242,1339]" pageId="27" pageNumber="121">
The two examined species, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Meigen, 1826)" baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1826" box="[515,916,1242,1268]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Eginia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ocypterata">
<emphasis box="[515,726,1243,1268]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="121">Eginia ocypterata</emphasis>
(Meigen, 1826)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Malloch, 1921" authorityName="Malloch" authorityYear="1921" box="[974,1393,1242,1268]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Xenotachina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallida">
<emphasis box="[974,1212,1242,1268]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="121">Xenotachina pallida</emphasis>
Malloch, 1921
</taxonomicName>
, have vein C extensively setulose dorsally (state 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[762,797,1277,1303]" pageId="27" pageNumber="121">A8</emphasis>
). The same state expectedly applies to all eginiine genera and species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
